    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "The main reason is that we may have different template for which we want to be able to identify the kind of state where into. In our current implementation this is the hits widgets, and when we have an result template the context of the template is bound to a single hit, whereas we bind the whole result object when we don't have any result. So the signature is different for the object itself. One solution is to pass the template key to the transformData function, but it makes the user have to handle the different signature using another parameter: \n\n``` js\ntransformData: (val, type) => {\n  if(type===\"result\") //blah\n  else(type===\"no-result\") //blouh\n}\n```\n\nIn the implementation we've chosen, the user provides two kind of transformData which removes this ugly boilerplate and also makes the signature of transformData more stable.\n",
    "created_at": "2015-11-19T17:59:35Z",
